[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] In computer programming, **create, read, update, and delete** (**CRUD**) are the four basic operations (actions) of persistent storage.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] CRUD is also sometimes used to describe user interface conventions that facilitate viewing, searching, and changing information using computer-based forms and reports.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] The term *CRUD* was likely first popularized in 1983 by James Martin in his book *Managing the data-base environment*.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] Data can be put in a *location/area* of a storage mechanism.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] Together these four operations make up the basic operations of storage management known as CRUD: *Create*, *Read*, *Update* and *Delete*.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] The acronym CRUD refers to the major operations which are implemented by databases.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] Each letter in the acronym can be mapped to a standard Structured Query Language (SQL) statement.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] Although relational databases are a common persistence layer in software applications, numerous other persistence layers exist.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] CRUD functionality can for example be implemented with document databases, object databases, XML databases, text files, or binary files.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] Some big data systems do not implement UPDATE, but have only a timestamped INSERT (journaling), storing a completely new version of the object each time.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] The acronym CRUD also appears in the discussion of RESTful APIs.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] In HTTP, the POST (create), GET (read), PUT (update), PATCH (partial update), and DELETE methods correspond to CRUD operations as they have storage management semantics, meaning that they let user agents directly manipulate the states of target resources.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] However, POST is not limited to resource creation and may also be used for process-oriented operations whose semantics exceed the scope of CRUD.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] CRUD is also relevant at the user interface level of most applications.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] For example, in address book software, the basic storage unit is an individual *contact entry*.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/create-read-update-and-delete] Because these operations are so fundamental, they are often documented and described under one comprehensive heading such as "contact management" or "document management" in general.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/data-binding] In computer programming, **data-binding** is a general technique that binds data sources from the provider and consumer together and synchronizes them.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/data-binding] This is usually done with two data/information sources with different languages, as in XML data binding and UI data binding.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/data-binding] In UI data binding, data and information objects of the same language, but different logic function are bound together (e.g., Java UI elements to Java objects).
[src:mass-assignment-defense/data-binding] In a data binding process, each data change is reflected automatically by the elements that are bound to the data.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/data-binding] The term data binding is also used in cases where an outer representation of data in an element changes, and the underlying data is automatically updated to reflect this change.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/data-binding] As an example, a change in a `TextBox` element could modify the underlying data value.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/mass-assignment-cheat-sheet] Software frameworks sometimes allow developers to automatically bind HTTP request parameters into program code variables or objects to make using that framework easier on developers.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/mass-assignment-cheat-sheet] Attackers can sometimes use this methodology to create new parameters that the developer never intended which in turn creates or overwrites new variable or objects in program code that was not intended.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/mass-assignment-cheat-sheet] This is called a **Mass Assignment** vulnerability.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/mass-assignment-cheat-sheet] In 2012, GitHub was hacked using mass assignment.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/mass-assignment-cheat-sheet] A user was able to upload his public key to any organization and thus make any subsequent changes in their repositories.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/mass-assignment-cheat-sheet] An architectural approach is to create Data Transfer Objects and avoid binding input directly to domain objects.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/mass-assignment-cheat-sheet] Only the fields that are meant to be editable by the user are included in the DTO.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/mass-assignment-cheat-sheet] Take a look here and here for the documentation.
