[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails' emergence in 2005 greatly influenced web app development, through innovative features such as seamless database table creations, migrations, and scaffolding of views to enable rapid application development.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails' influence on other web frameworks remains apparent today, with many frameworks in other languages borrowing its ideas, including Django in Python; Catalyst in Perl; Laravel, CakePHP and Yii in PHP; Grails in Groovy; Phoenix in Elixir; Play in Scala; and Sails.js in Node.js.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Well-known sites that use Ruby on Rails include Airbnb, Archive of Our Own, Crunchbase, Dribbble, GitHub, Twitch and Shopify.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] David Heinemeier Hansson extracted Ruby on Rails from his work on the project management tool Basecamp at the web application company 37signals.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Hansson first released Rails as open source in July 2004, but did not share commit rights to the project until February 2005.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] In August 2006, the framework reached a milestone when Apple announced that it would ship Ruby on Rails with Mac OS X v10.5 "Leopard", which was released in October 2007.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails version 2.3 was released on 15 March 2009, with major new developments in templates, engines, Rack and nested model forms.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Templates enable the developer to generate a skeleton application with custom gems and configurations.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Engines give developers the ability to reuse application pieces complete with routes, view paths and models.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] The Rack web server interface and Metal allow one to write optimized pieces of code that route around Action Controller.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] On 23 December 2008, Merb, another web application framework, was launched, and Ruby on Rails announced it would work with the Merb project to bring "the best ideas of Merb" into Rails 3, ending the "unnecessary duplication" across both communities.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Merb was merged with Rails as part of the Rails 3.0 release.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 3.1 was released on 31 August 2011, featuring Reversible Database Migrations, Asset Pipeline, Streaming, jQuery as default JavaScript library and newly introduced CoffeeScript and Sass into the stack.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 3.2 was released on 20 January 2012 with a faster development mode and routing engine (also known as Journey engine), Automatic Query Explain and Tagged Logging.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 3.2.x is the last version that supports Ruby 1.8.7.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 4.0 was released on 25 June 2013, introducing Russian Doll Caching, Turbolinks, and Live Streaming as well as making Active Resource, Active Record Observer and other components optional by splitting them as gems.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 4.1 was released on 8 April 2014, introducing Spring, Variants, Enums, Mailer previews, and secrets.yml.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 4.2 was released on 19 December 2014, introducing Active Job, asynchronous emails, Adequate Record, Web Console, and foreign keys.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 5.0 was released on 30 June 2016, introducing Action Cable, API mode, and Turbolinks 5.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 5.0.0.1 was released on 10 August 2016, with Exclusive use of rails CLI over Rake and support for Ruby version 2.2.2 and above.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 5.2 was released on 9 April 2018, introducing new features that include ActiveStorage, built-in Redis Cache Store, updated Rails Credentials and a new DSL that allows for configuring a Content Security Policy for an application.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 5.2.2 was released on 4 December 2018, introducing numerous bug fixes and several logic improvements.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 6.0 was released on 16 August 2019, making Webpack default, adding mailbox routing, a default online rich-text editor, parallel testing, multiple database support, mailer routing and a new autoloader.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 7.0 was released on 15 December 2021, replacing Node.js and Webpack with import maps for JavaScript management by default, replacing Turbolinks with a combination of Turbo and Stimulus, adding at-work encryption into Active Record, using Zeitwerk exclusively for code loading, and more.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 7.1 was released on 5 October 2023, Dockerfiles support using Kamal in order to deploy your application, authentication improvements, and now including support for Bun.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails 8.0.0 was released on 8 November 2024.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] This major release introduces fundamental shifts in Rails development, enabling individual developers to host and manage their applications independently without the need for a Platform-as-a-service.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] The update focuses on empowering single developers to handle all aspects of application deployment and management seamlessly.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails 8.1.0 was released on October 24, 2025.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Major features include Active Job Continuations, Structured Event Reporting, Local CI, and Markdown rendering.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] A revised maintenance policy was instituted in October 2024.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails evolves radically from release to release exploring the use of new technologies and adopting new standards on the Internet.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Some features are very stable in Ruby on Rails while some are replaced in favour of new techniques.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] The model–view–controller (MVC) pattern is the fundamental structure to organize application programming.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] In a default configuration, a *model* in the Ruby on Rails framework maps to a table in a database and to a Ruby file.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] For example, a model class *User* will usually be defined in the file 'user.rb' in the app/models directory, and linked to the table 'users' in the database.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] While developers are free to ignore this convention and choose differing names for their models, files, and database table, this is not common practice and is usually discouraged in accordance with the "convention-over-configuration" philosophy.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] A *controller* is a server-side component of Rails that responds to external requests from the web server to the application, by determining which view file to render.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] The controller may also have to query one or more models for information and pass these on to the view.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] For example, in an airline reservation system, a controller implementing a flight-search function would need to query a model representing individual flights to find flights matching the search, and might also need to query models representing airports and airlines to find related secondary data.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] The controller might then pass some subset of the flight data to the corresponding view, which would contain a mixture of static HTML and logic that use the flight data to create an HTML document containing a table with one row per flight.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] A controller may provide one or more actions.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] In Ruby on Rails, an action is typically a basic unit that describes how to respond to a specific external web-browser request.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Also, note that the controller/action will be accessible for external web requests only if a corresponding route is mapped to it.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails encourages developers to use RESTful routes, which include actions such as create, new, edit, update, destroy, show, and index.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] These mappings of incoming requests/routes to controller actions can be easily set up in the routes.rb configuration file.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] A *view* in the default configuration of Rails is an erb file, which is evaluated and converted to HTML at run-time.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Alternatively, many other templating systems can be used for views.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails includes tools that make common development tasks easier "out-of-the-box", such as scaffolding that can automatically construct some of the models and views needed for a basic website.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Also included are WEBrick, a simple Ruby web server that is distributed with Ruby, and Rake, a build system, distributed as a gem.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Together with Ruby on Rails, these tools provide a basic development environment.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails is most commonly not connected to the Internet directly, but through some front-end web server.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Mongrel was generally preferred over WEBrick in the early days, but it can also run on Lighttpd, Apache, Cherokee, Hiawatha, Nginx (either as a module – Phusion Passenger for example – or via CGI, FastCGI or mod ruby), and many others.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] From 2008 onward, Passenger replaced Mongrel as the most-used web server for Ruby on Rails.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby is also supported natively on IBM i.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails is also noteworthy for its extensive use of the JavaScript libraries Prototype and Script.aculo.us for scripting Ajax actions.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails 3.0 separates the markup of the page (which defines the structure of the page) from scripting (which determines functionality or logic of the page).
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] As of version 7.0, new Ruby on Rails applications come with the Hotwire family of JavaScript libraries installed by default.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Since version 2.0, Ruby on Rails offers both HTML and XML as standard output formats.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] The latter is the facility for RESTful web services.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails 3.1 introduced Sass as standard CSS templating.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] By default, the server uses Embedded Ruby in the HTML views, with files having an html.erb extension.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Rails supports swapping-in alternative templating languages, such as HAML and Mustache.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails 3.0 has been designed to work with Ruby 1.8.7, Ruby 1.9.2, and JRuby 1.5.2+; earlier versions are not supported.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails 3.2 is the last series of releases that support Ruby 1.8.7.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails is separated into various packages, namely ActiveRecord (an object-relational mapping system for database access), Action Pack, Active Support and Action Mailer.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Prior to version 2.0, Ruby on Rails also included the Action Web Service package that is now replaced by Active Resource.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Apart from standard packages, developers can make plugins to extend existing packages.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Earlier Rails supported plugins within their own custom framework; version 3.2 deprecates these in favor of standard Ruby "gems".
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails is often installed using RubyGems, a package manager which is included with current versions of Ruby.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Many free Unix-like systems also support installation of Ruby on Rails and its dependencies through their native package management system.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails is typically deployed with a database server such as MySQL or PostgreSQL, and a web server such as Apache running the Phusion Passenger module.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails is intended to emphasize *Convention over Configuration* (CoC), and the *Don't Repeat Yourself* (DRY) principle.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] The Rails Doctrine is an enduring enabler that guides the philosophy, design, and implementation of the Ruby on Rails framework.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] "Convention over Configuration" means a developer only needs to specify unconventional aspects of the application.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] For example, if there is a class *Sale* in the model, the corresponding table in the database is called *sales* by default.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] It is only if one deviates from this convention, such as calling the table "products sold", that the developer needs to write code regarding these names.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Generally, Ruby on Rails conventions lead to less code and less repetition.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] "Don't repeat yourself" means that information is located in a single, unambiguous place.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] For example, using the ActiveRecord module of Rails, the developer does not need to specify database column names in class definitions.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Instead, Ruby on Rails can retrieve this information from the database based on the class name.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] "Fat models, skinny controllers" means that most of the application logic should be placed within the model while leaving the controller as light as possible.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] HTML Over The Wire (Hotwire), Conceptual compression, and robust security mark Rails 7.0's approach to the One person framework.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] In March 2007, David Heinemeier Hansson applied to register three Ruby on Rails-related trademarks with the USPTO.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] These applications concern the phrase "RUBY ON RAILS", the word "RAILS", and the official Rails logo.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] In the summer of 2007, Hansson denied the publisher Apress permission to use the Ruby on Rails logo on the cover of a new Ruby on Rails book written by some authoritative community members.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] The episode gave rise to a polite protest in the Ruby on Rails community.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] The trademark of the logo was cancelled on 25 October 2019.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] In earlier days, Rails running on Matz's Ruby Interpreter (the *de facto* reference interpreter for Ruby) had been criticized for issues with scalability.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] These critiques often mentioned various Twitter outages in 2007 and 2008, which spurred Twitter's partial transition to Scala (which runs on the Java Virtual Machine) for their queueing system and other middleware.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] The user interface aspects of the site continued to run Ruby on Rails until 2011 when it was replaced due to concerns over performance.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] On the other hand, many Rails business application developers relied on system architecture design, including choices of database engine, cache configuration, and servers, to tackle scalability issues.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] The original author of Rails, David Heinemeier Hansson, criticized Twitter, saying that their problems scaling were the consequences of their own poor architectural decisions and not the fault of Rails.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] According to Hansson, blaming Rails for their troubles while making no contributions to the framework is ungrateful and unjust.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] In 2011, Gartner Research noted that despite criticisms and comparisons to Java, many high-profile consumer web firms are using Ruby on Rails to build scalable web applications.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Some of the largest sites running Ruby on Rails include Airbnb, Cookpad, GitHub, GitLab, Scribd, Shopify, and Basecamp.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] As of January 2016, it is estimated that more than 1.2 million web sites are running Ruby on Rails.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] In March 2012, security researcher Egor Homakov discovered a mass assignment vulnerability that allowed certain Rails applications to be remotely exploited, and demonstrated it by non-maliciously hacking GitHub after his earlier attempts at responsible disclosure were dismissed.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] On 24 September 2013, a session cookie persistence security flaw was reported in Ruby on Rails.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] In a default configuration, the entire session hash is stored within a session cookie known as *CookieStore*, allowing any authenticated session possessing the session cookie to log in as the target user at any time in the future.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] As a workaround, administrators are advised to configure cookies to be stored on the server using mechanisms such as *ActiveRecordStore*.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] Researchers Daniel Jackson and Joseph Near developed a data debugger they called "Space" that can analyze the data access of a Rails program and determine if the program properly adheres to rules regarding access restrictions.
[src:mass-assignment-defense/ruby-on-rails] On 15 April 2016, Near reported that an analysis of 50 popular Web applications using Space uncovered 23 previously unknown security flaws.
